[1;31;4m                            Bash Shortcuts                            [0;0m
[0;0m
[0;35medit[1;30m [0;36m[file][1;30m - [0;34mEdit a file using the default text editor[0;0m
[0;33msudoedit[1;30m [0;36m[file][1;30m - [0;34mEdit a file using sudo in a secure method[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-X-E[1;30m - [0;34mEdit command in an editor [0;36m([0;33mfc[0;36m command will edit last history)[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-Y[1;30m - [0;34mPastes text from the Bash clipboard[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-U[1;30m - [0;34mCuts text from the cursor to the beginning of the line [0;36m(Adds to clipboard)[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-K[1;30m - [0;34mCuts text from the cursor until the end of the line [0;36m(Adds to clipboard)[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-W[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;33mALT-BACKSPACE[1;30m - [0;34mCut word behind cursor [0;36m(Adds to clipboard)[0;0m
[0;33mEND CTRL-U[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;35mCTRL-Q[1;30m - [0;34mCuts and clears the entire line [0;36m(Add to clipboard)[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-A[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;33mHOME[1;30m - [0;34mMove cursor to the beginning of the line[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-E[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;33mEND[1;30m - [0;34mMove cursor to end of line[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-] [0;36mx[1;30m - [0;34mWhere [0;36mx[0;34m is any character, moves the cursor forward to next occurance of [0;36mx[0;0m
[0;33mALT-CTRL-] [0;36mx[1;30m - [0;34mWhere [0;36mx[0;34m is any character, moves the cursor to previous occurance of [0;36mx[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-XX[1;30m - [0;34mMove between start of line and current cursor position [0;36m(and back again)[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33mALT-T[1;30m - [0;34mSwaps the last two words[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-T[1;30m - [0;34mSwaps the last two characters[0;0m
[0;33mALT-U[1;30m - [0;34mCapitalize all characters in a word after the cursor[0;0m
[0;33mALT-L[1;30m - [0;34mLower case all characters in a word after the cursor[0;0m
[0;33mALT-.[1;30m - [0;34mUse the last word of the previous command[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33mhistory[1;30m - [0;34mShows your command line history[0;0m
[0;33m![0;36m10[1;30m - [0;34mRuns the command associated with the numbers listed by the history command[0;0m
[0;33mUp Arrow[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;33mCTRL-P[1;30m - [0;34mPrevious command in history[0;0m
[0;33mDown Arrow[1;30m [0;32mor[1;30m [0;33mCTRL-N[1;30m - [0;34mNext command in history[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-S[1;30m - [0;34mSearches the history forward[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-R[1;30m - [0;34mSearches the history backward [0;36m(reverse search)[0;0m
[0;33mALT-R[1;30m - [0;34mUndo any changes to a command from history[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-G[1;30m - [0;34mLeave the history searching mode without running the command[0;0m
[0;33m!![1;30m - [0;34mRepeats the last command [0;36m(i.e. [0;33msudo !![0;36m)[0;0m
[0;33m!$[1;30m - [0;34mRepeats only the argument from the last command[0;0m
[0;33m!*[1;30m - [0;34mRepeats all parameters from previous command[0;0m
[0;33m!^[1;30m - [0;34mRepeats only the first argument from the last command[0;0m
[0;33m![0;36mabc[1;30m - [0;34mExecute last command in history beginning with abc[0;0m
[0;33m![0;36mabc[0;33m:p[1;30m - [0;34mPrints last command in history beginning with abc[0;0m
[0;33mecho "!!" > [0;36m[file.sh][1;30m - [0;34mCreate a script of the last command[0;0m
[0;33m^[0;36mfind[0;33m^[0;36mreplace[1;30m - [0;34mRepeats the last command but replaces text[0;0m
[0;33mmv [0;36m/path/to/file[0;33m.{[0;36mtxt[0;33m,[0;36mxml[0;33m}[1;30m - [0;34mBrackets repeat the command with comma delimited changes[0;0m
[0;35mrepeat[1;30m - [0;34mRepeat a command n times[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-C[1;30m - [0;34mHalts the current command[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-Z[1;30m - [0;34mStops the current command [0;36m(resume with [0;33mfg[0;36m in foreground and [0;33mbg[0;36m in background)[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-S[1;30m - [0;34mPause terminal output [0;36m(program will keep running)[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-Q[1;30m - [0;34mRelease terminal output [0;36m(after being paused)[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-L[1;30m - [0;34mClear the screen[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-D[1;30m - [0;34mLog out[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;33m\[1;30m - [0;34mUse at the end of a line to continue a multi-line command[0;0m
[0;34m or use at the beginning of a command to bypass an alias.[0;0m
[0;33mCTRL-ALT-E[1;30m - [0;34mExpand an alias to it's actual code[0;0m
[0;0m
[0;32mTo stack multiple commands on one line:[0;0m
[0;33m&&[1;30m - [0;34mCommands separated by a double ampersand means AND and runs multiple[0;0m
[0;34m commands synchronously with each one running only if the last did not fail.[0;0m
[0;33m&[1;30m - [0;34mA single ampersand runs multiple commands asynchronously [0;36m(at the same time).[0;0m
[0;33m||[1;30m - [0;34mCommands separated by a double pipe means OR and runs multiple[0;0m
[0;34m commands synchronously with each one running only if the last command failed.[0;0m
[0;33m(cd /tmp && ls)[1;30m - [0;34mjump to directory, execute command, jump back[0;0m
